It's amazing how a game from the PS2 era runs so well on a port for PC, I'm so happy to see a game that I played through 10 years ago on newer platforms. Now for the good and bad. 

[u] The Good: [/u] [list]
[*]The game is entirely in 60 fps (haven't had a drop of frames ONCE);
[*]Cutscenes were optimized;
[*]Gameplay is fluid and leveling up weapons is no longer a giant grind or hassle;
[*]New textures are great;
[*] As a long time fan I thought the retry system would water down the experience (and pressure) of boss battles and hard areas, but let me tell you, getting one-shot by a Chaotic PKer after a long dungeon doesn't cause me to turn into a salt mine ever again, so well done!;
[*]Avatars battles have some nice upgrades [spoiler] you have a bar atop of the enemy representing his "stun meter", way better than to spam the long range attack forever. [/spoiler]
[/list]

[u] The Bad [/u] (they may be nitpicks): [list]
[*]Crimson VS is still kinda of just there.....no rhyme or reason to exist, and with card games like HS and Gwent, this one looks way outdated;
[*]We can see cutscenes from the previous volumes (which we couldn't in the PS2 games) but we can't continue with the Book of 1000's progression on different volumes? Makes 100% the games even harder since when you progress (on the next volume) you get gold instead of the previous volume bonus for achieving the goals (Wallpapers, Music for desktop and Movies), the additions were good but the system could've been done much better;
[*]Volume 1's balancing is still weird [spoiler] it's still a walk in the park until Tri-Edge if you do the areas from the e-mails before each arena match. [/spoiler]

When I get to Volume 4 I might come back and review it! This is mostly my view from what I played when revisiting Vol. 1 and 2.

