[i]Ever wanted to play an MMO game that isn't quite an MMO but still has features like a good story and great characters? Then .hack//G.U. Last Recode might just be for you! This remaster of a classic series is like a wet dream for most people who played the original on the PS2, and understandably so since this series is absolutely amazing! For this review, I will go over the pros and cons of the game that I have greatly enjoyed thus far.

(At this point, I would say a joke like "LINK START" to get this review rolling since they're both about MMOs, but that's unoriginal at this point and SAO isn't really good, so oh well.)[/i]

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

[h1]+ ᴘʀᴏꜱ[/h1]


[h1]+ Characters[/h1]
//One of the many great things about this series is the characters within it. It's weird that they are NPCs who are being portrayed as actuals players, but once you get used to that then it won't really bother you. Each character is unique with their own personality whether it's the friend who loves to observe the beauty around her and help her friends out, the twins sharing an account who act like total opposites, or the online ladiesman going out with people who are quite possibly guys crossplaying as girls. As for the character development, it's pretty incredible! Remember shows like SAO where the main character never really changes/develops as the show goes on? Lots of shows and games have been doing that recently and it gets pretty boring, but in Haseo's case he goes through TONS of development as the story goes on and it's a great change of pace to be quite honest.

[h1]+ Graphics[/h1]
//Even on the PS2, the graphics (especially in the cutscenes) were pretty good, but to have a remastered version of this come out is like a dream come true for the longtime fans of this series! When comparing the PS2 version with the Steam/PS4 versions, the difference is like night and day; the newer version is better in just about every way possible! Also, the system requirements aren't too demanding. I managed to get the game running smoothly on my laptop [u][url=https://www.cnet.com/products/dell-inspiron-3558-15-6-core-i3-5015u-4-gb-ram-1-tb-hdd-english/specs/](Dell Inspiron 3558)[/url][/u] although I really had to tweak with the settings for it to work out... Nevertheless, I managed to get it working well.

[h1]+ Soundtrack[/h1]
//To say the least, this game has an amazing soundtrack! I love how it can be relaxing at places like the desktop and then can get intense/energetic in fights, especially in boss battles or in the Arena. The game has a great variety of songs that really helps for setting the mood which is something I appreciate for a heavily story-based game. (I couldn't find a video featuring the whole soundtrack, so this'll have to do.)

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jy0KGY7DKCM

[h1]+ Story[/h1]
//The story is definetly one of the games greatest selling points! It's suprisingly deep and is very consistent with it being based off of an "online game" and all. You'd expect it to be boring, but with how things play out at the start (especially within the first few cutscenes), I can guarantee that a good number of people will be interested with how the story plays out. (Also, for those new to the series, there's an [u][url=https://myanimelist.net/anime/873/hack__Roots]anime[/url][/u] that goes through the events before the start of Vol.//1, which definetly adds some more depth to the story. There's also manga revealing who Haseo is in real life, but that's not absolutely necessary to check out.) And with the addition of a fourth volume that's exclusive to Steam and PS4, it'll be especially worth the price!

//In short, if you want a game with a great story filled with tons of emotion that'll last for +100 hours, then I would highly recommend you check this game out.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━


[h1]- ᴄᴏɴꜱ[/h1]


[h1]- Combat[/h1]
//While the combat can be fun for some people, it's definetly not the reason people love this game as much as they do. It picks up as the game goes on, but it can still be repetitive and boring for most people. Combat mostly consists of Haseo using multiple weapons such as dual swords, a great sword that's like a chain saw, a scythe, dual-weilding guns, etc. Each weapon has one combo through mashing one button and also has a charge attack which deals a great amount of damage. The most interesting mechanics are that you can freely switch between these weapons in a fight and each weapon has their own set of skills that can be used at any time as long as the player has enough SP to activate it. However, you only unlock these skills by using that specific weapon through battles overtime. I personally didn't mind the combat and still found it to be quite fun, but I just thought I'd bring this up since the combat isn't quite for everyone.

[h1]- Level Designs[/h1]
//Even though the graphics and the backgrounds surrounding the maps are quite amazing, the designs for the dungeons are pretty stale. They seem pretty uninspired since they mostly consist of boxes and large amounts of straight lines for the level's layout. As for the hub world, it's nowhere near as bad as the dungeons but it could be better in my opinion. There's a good amount of things to do and places to buy items in the town, but I feel as if a lot of the alleys are a little too.... empty. I just wish that there were more things going on around the towns. 

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

[h1]Final Verdict[/h1]
//If you want a great story but value a games level designs and combat system, then this is a [u]7 through 9/10[/u] depending on how you look at it. However, if you don't mind the inconsistencies and focus mainly on the captivating story, then this game is easily a [u]10/10[/u]. It's a solid port for an amazing series and that's something all fans should be thankful for. After having waited for this remaster to come out for a while, I can safely say that it was well worth the wait.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
